ce:section.ce:para:
In this study, the authors utilized biomass waste of peach leaves for the extraction of CQDs. Then, they incorporated Bi2WO6 on the as obtained CQDs nanomaterials. The authors applied X–ray diffraction (XRD), Fourier transform infrared (FTIR), field emission scanning electron microscopy (FESEM), transmission electron microscope (TEM), X–ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS), HR–TEM (high–resolution transmission electron microscope), N2 adsorption–desorption isotherms, ultraviolet–visible diffuse reflectance spectroscopy (UV–vis–DRS) and photochemical properties to prove the successful synthesis of CQDs-based S–scheme heterojunctions [103]. From these techniques, the authors indicated that the obtained CQDS display a spherical size of 4.73 nm and lattice spacing of 0.327 nm. Additionally, Bi2WO6 presented 2D irregular petal–like structure composed of small particles with diameters ranging of 50 to 80 nm. With the addition of CQDs, the 3.0 wt% CQDs/Bi2WO6 exhibited a 2D regular sheet–like structure with diameters ranging from 80 to 150 nm and a different lattice spacings of 0.272 and 0.327 nm, which respectively correspond to the (002) crystal face of CQDs and the (002) lattice plane of Bi2WO6. Moreover, the different diffraction peaks of 3.0 wt%CQDs/Bi2WO6 at 28.3, 32.8/32.9, 47.1, 56.0, 58.5 and 68.8° can be attributed to the (131), (002), (202), (133), (262) and (400) planes of Bi2WO6. Consequently, they demonstrated that the addition of raw CQDs affects the crystal orientation of Bi2WO6. The C1s spectrum of 3 wt%CQDs/Bi2WO6 is divided into four peaks, the peaks positioned at 284.8, 286.2, 288.0, and 288.9 eV, respectively, corresponding to C–C/C = C, C-O, Bi–O–C, and C = O bonds. In this work, the authors utilized the as prepared S–scheme CQDs/Bi2WO6 heterojunction for tetracycline (TC) degradation under visible light irradiation. They utilized DFT study Fukui function calculations, EPR spectroscopy, and LC–MS analysis to get an insight about the degradation pathways of TC. Furthermore, the toxicity of the as–obtained photocatalyst was evaluated by highlighting its impacts on the surviving bacterial colonies density (E.Coli cultivation).The authors indicated that effective separation and migration of the photoproduced charges greatly enhance the photocatalytic efficiency of the 3.0 wt%CQDs/Bi2WO6 photocatalyst. Furthermore, the photodegradation efficiency of TC by 3.0 wt%CQDs/Bi2WO6 heterojunction reached 89.0 % within 40 min but without total degradation of tetracycline. They indicated that there are two pathways for TC degradation (i.e., N–demethylation, ring–opening reaction and dehydroxylation reactions) to obtain the different by–products of TC molecule (Fig. 11
                     ). Moreover, the growth curves of E. coli demonstrate the negligible influence of 3.0 wt%CQDs/Bi2WO6 heterojunction on bacteria, suggesting that 3.0 wt%CQDs/Bi2WO6 heterojunction cannot further contaminate the environment during the photocatalytic degradation of TC. They demonstrated that the 2C, 16C, 20O, 23O, 26O, and 28 N positions in TC molecule exhibit high f0 values, suggesting that these sites can be attacked by •OH radicals. Additionally, the ESP distributions point–out that the regions around 32O in the hydroxyl group, 20O in the carbonyl group, and 25 N in the acylamine group for TC may be attacked by the negatively charged superoxide radicals •O2
                     – (Fig. 11).
